The Gauss map can be defined for [hypersurfaces](/Hypersurface) in R n as a map from a hypersurface to the unit sphere S n &#8722; 1 &#160;⊆&#160; R n .

*(Naturally, we can't be confined to mere surfaces in R 3. That would be far too pedestrian.)* The concept of the Gauss map extends quite naturally to higher dimensions. For a [hypersurface](/Hypersurface) in [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space) R n – which is essentially a (n-1)-dimensional "surface" embedded within an n-dimensional space (think of a 2D surface in 3D space, or a 3D "surface" in 4D space) – the Gauss map can be defined in a completely analogous manner. Each point on this [hypersurface](/Hypersurface) still possesses a unique [normal direction](/Normal_direction), which can be represented as a [unit vector](/Unit_vector). This [unit vector](/Unit_vector) is then mapped to a point on the (n-1)-dimensional [unit sphere](/Unit_sphere), denoted as S n &#8722; 1 , which is itself a subset of R n . The core principle remains identical: local orientation information from a complex manifold is projected onto a simpler, spherical manifold. It's a testament to the robustness of the initial idea, or perhaps, the sheer stubbornness of mathematicians in applying a good trick wherever they can.

