*(Oh, now it gets truly interesting, or at least, more abstract. Brace yourself.)* Going even further, for a general oriented k-[submanifold](/Submanifold) embedded within R n – meaning a k-dimensional "surface" within an n-dimensional [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space) – the Gauss map takes on a slightly different, more sophisticated form. Instead of mapping to a simple [unit sphere](/Unit_sphere), its target space becomes the oriented [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian) G̃ k,n . What is this mystical [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian)? It is, quite simply, the space that comprises *all* possible oriented k-dimensional planes (or subspaces) passing through the origin in R n .

In this more generalized setting, at each point on the k-[submanifold](/Submanifold), we don't just have a single normal vector. Instead, we have an entire k-dimensional [tangent subspace](/Tangent_space) that "touches" the submanifold at that point, and an (n-k)-dimensional normal subspace that is [orthogonal](/Orthogonal) to it. The Gauss map, in this scenario, takes a point on the submanifold and maps it to its oriented [tangent subspace](/Tangent_space) within the [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian). Alternatively, and equivalently, one could map the point to its oriented normal subspace. This equivalence is due to the fact that the [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian) of k-planes is isomorphic to the [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian) of (n-k)-planes (G̃ k,n ≅ G̃ n-k,n) via the operation of taking the [orthogonal complement](/Orthogonal_complement).

To bring this back to something vaguely comprehensible, consider our original case: a 2D surface in [Euclidean 3-space](/Euclidean_space) (k=2, n=3). Here, an oriented 2-plane (the [tangent plane](/Tangent_plane)) is uniquely characterized by an oriented 1-line (the normal line), which itself is defined by a [unit normal vector](/Unit_vector). The [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian) of oriented 1-planes in R n is isomorphic to S n-1 (G̃ 1,n ≅ S n-1). So, for k=2, n=3, mapping to the 1-plane (normal vector) in R 3 is equivalent to mapping to S 2. This neatly ties the generalized definition back to the familiar, less anxiety-inducing definition for surfaces in R 3. It's almost as if it was designed to be consistent.

Finally, the notion of Gauss map can be generalized to an oriented submanifold X of dimension k in an oriented ambient [Riemannian manifold](/Riemannian_manifold) M of dimension n . In that case, the Gauss map then goes from X to the set of tangent k -planes in the [tangent bundle](/Tangent_bundle) TM . The target space for the Gauss map N is a [Grassmann bundle](/Grassmann_bundle) built on the tangent bundle TM . In the case where
