, the tangent bundle is trivialized (so the Grassmann bundle becomes a map to the Grassmannian), and we recover the previous definition.

*(And now, for the pièce de résistance, the ultimate generalization. Because why stop at [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space) when you can wander into the glorious, curved realms of [Riemannian manifolds](/Riemannian_manifold)?)* The final, most abstract generalization of the Gauss map takes us beyond the flat, predictable landscape of [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space) and into the curved, intrinsic geometry of an oriented k-[submanifold](/Submanifold) X embedded within an oriented ambient [Riemannian manifold](/Riemannian_manifold) M of dimension n. A [Riemannian manifold](/Riemannian_manifold) is a space where every point has a well-defined notion of distance and angle, but it's not necessarily "flat" like [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space). Think of the surface of the Earth, which is a 2D manifold embedded in 3D [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space), but has its own intrinsic curved geometry.

In this highly general setting, the Gauss map N transforms a point on the submanifold X to an element within the set of tangent k-planes in the [tangent bundle](/Tangent_bundle) TM of the ambient manifold M. The [tangent bundle](/Tangent_bundle) TM itself is a manifold that bundles together all the [tangent spaces](/Tangent_space) at every point of M. Essentially, for each point *q* in M, there's a [tangent space](/Tangent_space) TqM, and the [tangent bundle](/Tangent_bundle) collects all these TqM's into a single, larger structure. The target space for this most generalized Gauss map is not a simple [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian) anymore, but rather a [Grassmann bundle](/Grassmann_bundle) built upon the [tangent bundle](/Tangent_bundle) TM. This [Grassmann bundle](/Grassmann_bundle) essentially tells you, for every point *q* in M, what are all the possible k-planes that can exist in the [tangent space](/Tangent_space) TqM.

It's a dizzying level of abstraction, I know. But the beauty, if you can call it that, is in its consistency. When the ambient manifold M happens to be the flat [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space) R n , the [tangent bundle](/Tangent_bundle) is said to be "trivialized" – meaning it can be thought of as a simple product of M and R n . In this special case, the [Grassmann bundle](/Grassmann_bundle) simplifies back into the familiar [Grassmannian](/Grassmannian), and we recover the previous definition for submanifolds in [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space). So, even when things get ridiculously complicated, there's always a path back to the basics. Just try not to get lost on the way.

## Total curvature

